  <h2>What Is Biofloc Technology?</h2>
  <p>
    Biofloc technology (BFT) is a sustainable aquaculture practice that converts waste into supplemental feed through the cultivation of beneficial microorganisms. Instead of relying solely on external feed and frequent water exchanges, biofloc systems create a living ecosystem where bacteria, algae, and other microorganisms form small particles (flocs) that shrimp and fish can eat.
  </p>
  <p>
    The result? Better water quality, reduced feed costs, and higher productivity — all while using less water.
  </p>

  <h2>How Biofloc Systems Work</h2>

  <h3>The Nitrogen Cycle in Biofloc</h3>
  <p>
    In a biofloc system, the nitrogen cycle works differently than in traditional ponds:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Shrimp excrete ammonia</li>
    <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Heterotrophic bacteria consume ammonia and convert it to microbial protein</li>
    <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> The protein-rich bacteria form floc particles</li>
    <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Shrimp consume the flocs as supplemental feed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This is the key innovation — waste becomes food instead of a pollutant.
  </p>

  <h3>Carbon-to-Nitrogen Ratio</h3>
  <p>
    The critical factor in biofloc systems is maintaining a carbon-to-nitrogen (C:N) ratio above 15:1. This ensures heterotrophic bacteria have enough carbon to consume all available nitrogen. Without sufficient carbon, ammonia accumulates.
  </p>

  <h2>Setting Up Your Biofloc System</h2>

  <h3>1. Pond Preparation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Ensure pond is clean and properly limed</li>
    <li>Apply Soil Renew to prepare the bottom</li>
    <li>Install adequate aeration (minimum 30 HP/hectare)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2. Water Fill and Initial Treatment</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Fill pond with clean water</li>
    <li>Apply BioFloc Starter to introduce the carbon source and initial bacteria</li>
    <li>Maintain temperature above 25°C (77°F) for optimal bacterial growth</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3. Establishing the Floc</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Begin aeration immediately — biofloc systems require continuous aeration</li>
    <li>Monitor floc volume using an Imhoff cone</li>
    <li>Target floc volume: 5-10 ml/L</li>
    <li>Maintain C:N ratio above 15:1 by adding carbohydrate sources as needed</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>4. Stocking</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Wait until floc is established (typically 7-10 days)</li>
    <li>Stock at lower density than traditional systems (40-60 PL/m² for shrimp)</li>
    <li>Reduce feed ration by 20-30% since flocs provide supplemental nutrition</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Key Water Parameters</h2>
  <p>
    Biofloc systems require careful monitoring of specific parameters:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> 25-32°C (optimal for bacterial growth)</li>
    <li><strong>pH:</strong> 7.5-8.5 (maintain with lime as needed)</li>
    <li><strong>Dissolved oxygen:</strong> Above 4 mg/L at all times</li>
    <li><strong>Alkalinity:</strong> Above 150 mg/L (bacteria consume alkalinity)</li>
    <li><strong>Floc volume:</strong> 5-10 ml/L (measure with Imhoff cone)</li>
    <li><strong>Turbidity:</strong> 150-250 NTU (indicates healthy floc)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Daily Management Tasks</h2>

  <h3>Every Day</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Check aeration equipment — backup power is essential</li>
    <li>Measure floc volume with Imhoff cone</li>
    <li>Test pH, dissolved oxygen, and ammonia</li>
    <li>Observe shrimp behavior and feed consumption</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Every 2-3 Days</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Test alkalinity — add lime if below 150 mg/L</li>
    <li>Measure floc settleability</li>
    <li>Adjust feed based on consumption</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Weekly</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Apply AquaBio Pro to maintain beneficial bacteria</li>
    <li>Test nitrite and nitrate levels</li>
    <li>Check floc composition under microscope if available</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Challenges and Solutions</h2>

  <h3>Problem: High Ammonia</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Cause:</strong> Insufficient carbon or low bacterial population
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Solution:</strong> Increase carbon source (molasses, rice bran), apply BioFloc Starter, reduce feeding temporarily
  </p>

  <h3>Problem: Low Dissolved Oxygen</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Cause:</strong> High floc density or aeration failure
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Solution:</strong> Increase aeration, reduce floc volume by partial water exchange, check equipment
  </p>

  <h3>Problem: Floc Not Forming</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Cause:</strong> Low temperature, low C:N ratio, or insufficient bacteria
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Solution:</strong> Ensure temperature above 25°C, increase carbon source, apply BioFloc Starter
  </p>

  <h3>Problem: pH Dropping</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Cause:</strong> Bacteria consuming alkalinity
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Solution:</strong> Add agricultural lime (CaCO₃) or sodium bicarbonate to maintain pH above 7.5
  </p>

  <h2>Benefits of Biofloc Technology</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Water savings:</strong> 70-90% less water usage than traditional systems</li>
    <li><strong>Feed savings:</strong> 20-30% reduction in feed costs from supplemental floc nutrition</li>
    <li><strong>Higher density:</strong> Can support 50-100% higher stocking densities</li>
    <li><strong>Better biosecurity:</strong> Closed systems reduce pathogen introduction</li>
    <li><strong>Environmental benefit:</strong> Minimal water discharge</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>
  <p>
    Biofloc technology requires more management skill than traditional ponds, but the benefits are significant. Start with a small trial pond, learn the system, and expand as you gain experience.
  </p>
